Inflation, in Europe, has eroded on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 countries of the euro area was more significant than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community statistics office located in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the principal interest rate by saying that lowering interest rates, with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation in order not to have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market shares increased by 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the global oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 in 2008, this year to 2.5 per cent, but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the inflation rate over 12 months remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the central rate twice in 2008.
