Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, unlike this year's VAT rate did not increase.
Article de Daily Economy (Economie quotidienne)
This year, in the Budaörs trade triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of significantly more than one thousand forints was seen in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had “already flown” in major grocery stores last December, have not risen sharply from the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items bought well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Unicum and live fish prices remained almost at last year's level, but turkey, walnut and turkey prices have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the registered two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints per registered bottle included.
Only this year, in terms of Daily Cart, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive one is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process confused the trade, the hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products so they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of 1,720 forints in 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the cheapest prices increased by 1,284 forints as well.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic rise in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the data of KSH: for some primary necessities, the Institute of Statistics found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already quite expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to accept the brutal rise in prices also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-lived foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less significant in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save money on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred at the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have been unable to perform a major operation due to the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resisting pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resisting pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
SA infections (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or septicaemia, in elderly, low-weight patients or those with a weakened organism.
According to the director of the hospital J<0xC3><0xA1>nos, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only or we are not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
The sampling of the sample is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection manifests mainly in hospitals and in seniors’ residences, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA-carrying patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only arise if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has stringent recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, in other words, microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, important gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by inhalation of droplets and by contact, however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (as well as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
