Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus resembles Earth more than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind gusts at the poles, similar to those appearing in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning strikes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today brought the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: flashes on Venus explode at an altitude of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Magaenti "Christopher Russel of the University of Los Sicily in California.
According to the famous cyprin theory, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there should be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental issue of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, as no probe was on its way to the exploration of this planet since the 1990s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more than initially assumed.
Thus, in addition to the wind turbines already known at the north pole, the researchers found a cloud turbine at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly remembers Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
