Von Beust has criticised the cancellation of the Olympics.
The mayor's resignation with Hamburg's candidacy for the Summer Olympics has clashed in politics and the economy with critical virulence.
Many want to continue to fight for the Games on the waterfront.
But Von Beust calls for realism in the appreciation of chances.
Hans-Jörg Schmidt-Trenz, chief executive of the Hamburg Chamber of Commerce, on Wednesday described an abandonment as "bad for the local economy".
In recent times, no other project had deployed as much motivating forces in the city as the idea of the Olympics.
"Without this objective, the political-sports momentum could not have been maintained in the same measure."
Schmidt-Trenz invites the Senate not to bury the project, but to find a new starting point for it in the longer term, "which takes as its starting point another modified agenda".
Mayor Ole von Beust said on Wednesday that Hamburg’s Olympic ambitions were unrealistic at least until 2028.
"It's not Hamburg that decides to run for the Olympics, but the German Olympic Sports Federation," Von Beust told WELT ONLINE.
He refers to the expected decision of the Sports Federation at the beginning of December, about Munich’s candidacy for the 2018 Winter Games.
This preference means for us that, in the time frame we had planned until 2028 so far, we will have no chance."
However, the dream is not definitively a thing of the past, Von Beust said.
The Hamburg Sports Federation (HSB) regretted Beust’s statements.
From this it would seem that Hamburg no longer wants to apply for the Olympic Games in the next 25 years.
“It’s too early to close an opportunity, burying the projects already now,” said HSB President Günter Ploss on Wednesday.
An abandonment of the candidacy would further contradict the statements of the head of the Senate on the occasion of the welcome to the plenary assembly of the German Federation of Higher Sports Schools.
There, Von Beust would have qualified Hamburg’s 2015 Universiade bid as “not a substitute” for the Olympic Games in Hamburg.
The Federation of Higher Sports Schools had first in the past weeks named Hamburg as a candidate city.
The mayor’s SPD faction has accused the Senate of not using this precious time in building housing in Hamburg.
“The development of Little Grasbrook has been rejected by the Senate for years because it played the Olympic card and excluded housing construction,” SPD delegates Carola Veit and Jan Quast said.
While the SPD has always called for Little Grasbrook to have a plan integrated into the Olympics and a subsequent use of housing, the CDU would have relied exclusively on the "Event factor".
The bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics in Hamburg, for its part, would have raised great enthusiasm.
Hamburg, however, had broken up against Leipzig.
