The one who connects the concepts of Sweden and the wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the eighty Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today results in a great result that "six cents" of the "Brillo-Boxes" are the "Circles" of the "Brillo-Boxes", of which the "Circle" of the "Brillo-Boxes" is a direct.
The ancient history is entwined, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
It was not a question of works of art, but rather of their models, of exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered right into the history of art and auctions, as Andy Warhol's original Brillo-Boxes authorized, with the appellation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén wrongly claimed later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later cede to him.
In fact, the 105 boxes of Hultén were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum’s six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and punctured in white.
The texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a background layer on the laminate panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York's 'Modern' and 'Modern' Art Authentication Board' will not be a different decision.
Already in July, the Authentication Board has of course announced that it will investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers of Manila are abandoning
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers give up, the same ones who had retreated to a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he would not be able to answer for any bloodshed.
Loyal soldiers in power had raided the hotel shortly before using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had cut themselves off for hours in the building.
About half of them were held in court on Wednesday due to an attempted putsch that was missed in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse with about 30 supporters.
The military police officers, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favor and had joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops in power circled the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have enough,” Trillans said.
“We’re calling on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded the Scout Rangers’ elite unit, said that other units of the army would soon join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The Manila Financial District has been the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke out almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
